    <h1>Milk Seller to Scientist</h1>
    <p>
      Dr. G.D. Naidu started life as a milk delivery boy in Tamil Nadu, riding a bicycle for miles to support his family. But even during those humble days, he had a burning curiosity for machines and invention. With no formal education in engineering, he dismantled and rebuilt engines just to understand how they worked.
    </p>
    <p>
      Over time, he became one of India’s greatest inventors—developing India’s first indigenous motor, hair clippers, and even an electric razor. He eventually earned the title “Edison of India.” From selling milk to mentoring engineers, Naidu’s life reminds us that genius can rise from even the most modest beginnings.
    </p>

